{% extends "layouts/base.njk" %}
{% import "partials/_demo.njk" as ui %}

{% block title %}Breakpoints · Stisla{% endblock %}

{% block content %}
  <header>
    <h1>Breakpoints</h1>
    <p class="lead">Six named viewport widths, mobile-first.</p>
  </header>

  <section>
    <p>Stisla uses the same six breakpoints as Bootstrap 5 so the grid classes (<code>.col-md-6</code>, <code>.container-lg</code>) and the Sass mixins (<code>media-up</code>, <code>media-down</code>) read the same map. Every media rule applies from the named width upward unless the mixin says otherwise. That is the mobile-first default.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>The breakpoints</h2>
    <p>There are six tiers. <code>xs</code> is the implicit baseline; any rule that doesn&rsquo;t name a breakpoint applies at every width.</p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Name</th>
          <th>Min-width</th>
          <th>Typical device</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><code>xs</code></td><td>0</td><td>Portrait phones</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>sm</code></td><td>576px</td><td>Landscape phones</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>md</code></td><td>768px</td><td>Tablets</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>lg</code></td><td>992px</td><td>Small laptops</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>xl</code></td><td>1200px</td><td>Desktops</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>xxl</code></td><td>1400px</td><td>Wide desktops</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>The infix convention</h2>
    <p>Every responsive class (grid columns, gutters, alignment utilities, display utilities, font sizes) uses the breakpoint name as an infix between the property prefix and the value. You&rsquo;ll see this in <code>.col-md-6</code>, <code>.gx-lg-3</code>, <code>.d-md-flex</code>, <code>.fs-xl-5</code>, and so on.</p>
    <p><code>xs</code> is the implicit baseline and has <em>no</em> infix. There&rsquo;s no <code>.col-xs-6</code>; the bare <code>.col-6</code> is the <code>xs</code> form. Every other tier (<code>sm</code>, <code>md</code>, <code>lg</code>, <code>xl</code>, <code>xxl</code>) gets a <code>-{name}-</code> segment. The Sass helper <code>breakpoint-infix($name)</code> returns the empty string for <code>xs</code> and <code>-sm</code>, <code>-md</code>, &hellip; for everything else.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Sass mixins</h2>
    <p>Four mixins cover the common shapes. Import the foundation file and call them with a breakpoint name.</p>
    {% call ui.code(lang='scss') %}
    @use 'stisla/scss/foundation/breakpoints' as *;

    .example {
      // At or above the named breakpoint.
      @include media-up(md) {
        // applies from 768px upward
      }

      // Below the named breakpoint (note: 0.02px adjustment to avoid
      // overlap with media-up at the boundary).
      @include media-down(md) {
        // applies up to 767.98px
      }

      // Between two named breakpoints, inclusive on both ends.
      @include media-between(sm, lg) {
        // applies from 640px through 1279.98px
      }

      // Only the named breakpoint (no overlap above or below).
      @include media-only(md) {
        // applies from 768px through 1023.98px
      }
    }
    {% endcall %}
    <p>The <code>media-breakpoint-up</code> / <code>media-breakpoint-down</code> spellings still work as shims, but the short forms above are the canonical names.</p>

    <h3>What they compile to</h3>
    <p>The four mixins produce these media queries at each tier. <code>media-down</code> and <code>media-only</code> subtract <code>0.02px</code> from the next breakpoint to avoid overlapping with the matching <code>media-up</code> at the boundary (a one-pixel limitation of <code>min-width</code> + <code>max-width</code>).</p>
    {% call ui.code(lang='css') %}
    /* media-up */
    @media (min-width: 640px)  { ... }  /* sm */
    @media (min-width: 768px)  { ... }  /* md */
    @media (min-width: 1024px) { ... }  /* lg */
    @media (min-width: 1280px) { ... }  /* xl */
    @media (min-width: 1536px) { ... }  /* xxl */

    /* media-down */
    @media (max-width: 639.98px)  { ... }  /* sm */
    @media (max-width: 767.98px)  { ... }  /* md */
    @media (max-width: 1023.98px) { ... }  /* lg */
    @media (max-width: 1279.98px) { ... }  /* xl */
    @media (max-width: 1535.98px) { ... }  /* xxl */

    /* media-only(md) */
    @media (min-width: 768px) and (max-width: 1023.98px) { ... }

    /* media-between(sm, lg) */
    @media (min-width: 640px) and (max-width: 1279.98px) { ... }
    {% endcall %}
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Why media queries can&rsquo;t read CSS vars</h2>
    <p>The breakpoint table lives as Sass values. <code>@media (min-width: var(--bp-md))</code> doesn&rsquo;t work in any browser because CSS variables resolve per-element while a media rule has to evaluate at the document level before any element exists. So breakpoints stay in Sass; gutters, container max-widths, and the rest live on CSS vars.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Override the map</h2>
    <p>Set <code>$breakpoints</code> before importing the foundation. The grid, container, and every <code>media-*</code> mixin call read the override.</p>
    {% call ui.code(lang='scss') %}
    // _my-overrides.scss
    $breakpoints: (
      xs:  0,
      sm:  480px,
      md:  768px,
      lg:  1024px,
      xl:  1440px,
      xxl: 1920px,
    );

    @use 'stisla/scss/bundles/stisla';
    {% endcall %}
    <p>Renaming or removing a tier breaks the grid utility classes (there's no <code>.col-2xl-6</code> if you don't have <code>2xl</code>). Add tiers; don't subtract.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>RTL</h2>
    <p>Viewport size is independent of writing direction. The breakpoint table and every <code>media-*</code> mixin work the same way whether <code>&lt;html&gt;</code> carries <code>dir="ltr"</code> or <code>dir="rtl"</code>. Layout primitives like the grid, container, and offsets are authored with logical properties so they flip automatically. See the <a href="/grid">Grid page</a> for the full surface.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Customization</h2>
    <p>Two Sass maps drive every responsive behaviour. Override before importing.</p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Variable</th>
          <th>Default</th>
          <th>Use</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>$breakpoints</code></td>
          <td>xs 0, sm 576px, md 768px, lg 992px, xl 1200px, xxl 1400px</td>
          <td>Named viewport widths used by every <code>media-*</code> mixin and every responsive class suffix.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>$container-max-widths</code></td>
          <td>sm 540px, md 720px, lg 960px, xl 1140px, xxl 1320px</td>
          <td>Maximum content widths the <code>.container</code> classes clamp to at each breakpoint. See <a href="/grid">Grid</a>.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>
{% endblock %}
